{
    "analysis": "We extracted metric aggregates, computed global thresholds (P95/P5 and then looser P90/P10), and detected anomalies in the incident window (2021-03-06 03:30–04:00 UTC+8). Initial strict P95/P5 detection produced many trivial flags (constant-series equals threshold). Loosening to P90/P10 surfaced meaningful breaches: the highest-severity candidates are apache01 (OSLinux-CPU_CPU-0_SingleCpuidle) with a CPU idle collapse at 2021-03-06 ~03:37 (severity ~1936), IG01 (OSLinux-CPU_CPU-2_SingleCpuidle) with collapse at ~03:30–03:40 (severity ~822), and Mysql01 (InnoDB log/write related metrics) with spikes at ~03:30 (severity up to ~67). Tomcat02 also showed CPU anomalies ~03:57. We then extracted fault runs (consecutive anomalous minute points) for the top candidate groups: runs are mostly short (1–2 minutes). Some runs have NaN severity because thresholds or min values are zero (e.g., MySQL metrics with zero baseline), so ratio-based severity is undefined for those. At this stage we have multiple faulty components (node-level CPU saturation on apache01 and IG01, DB write spikes on Mysql01) within the failure window; to localize the single root cause we must correlate these metric faults with trace behavior (to find propagation/downstream faulty service) and with logs (to find resource-level errors or service error counts). Traces can tell us ordering in call chains (which faulty service is most downstream and thus likely the root cause) and whether request latencies or counts dropped/peaked around the candidate fault start times. Therefore the next step is to search trace telemetry for anomalies involving the top candidate components during the same incident window, using global thresholds computed across the full trace series before filtering by time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Scan trace.csv for trace groups related to the top metric candidates. Specifically: consider trace rows where the trace_name string contains any of these substrings: 'IG01','apache01','Mysql01','Tomcat02','Tomcat01'. For each matching (cmdb_id, trace_name) group, compute the global P95 and P5 from the full available series (do NOT filter by time for threshold calculation). Then filter trace rows to the incident window 2021-03-06 03:30 to 2021-03-06 04:00 (UTC+8) and mark anomalies where value >= global_P95 or value <= global_P5. Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of groups that have at least one anomaly in-window with these columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, group_count, global_p95, global_p5, anomalies_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, min_value_in_window, max_value_in_window. Sort by anomalies_count_in_window desc then max_value_in_window desc. Keep outputs compact (<=20 rows) and do not return raw time series." }

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: aggregated telemetry, computed global thresholds (P95/P5 then loosened to P90/P10), detected anomalies in metrics and traces within the incident window (2021-03-06 03:30–04:00 UTC+8), and extracted fault runs for top candidates. Key findings so far: multiple components show anomalous behavior starting at or shortly after 03:30 — notably IG01 (CPU/core idle anomalies and trace.to_Tomcat01.row_count anomalies at ~03:30–03:31), Mysql01 (Innodb write/log spikes and Aborted Clients at ~03:30), Tomcat01/Tomcat02 (trace row_count anomalies from IG and CPU anomalies), and apache01 (CPU WIO and a CPU idle collapse around 03:33–03:37). Severity scores (ratio-based) rank apache01 and IG01 highest (very large up/down ratios), with Mysql01 also notable. However some MySQL metrics give NaN severity because of zero baselines. Traces show elevated row_counts for Tomcat↔MG/IG interactions beginning ~03:30–03:32, which aligns with the metric faults. To localize a single root cause we must identify the earliest significant fault across sources per candidate component, and determine whether that faulty component is upstream or downstream in anomalous traces. The timeline we obtained already lists per-component per-source earliest anomalies (metrics at 03:30 for IG01 and Mysql01; trace anomalies at 03:31 for IG→Tomcat paths). We need a compact cross-source earliest-per-component ranking (which source produced the absolute earliest anomaly for each candidate, plus whether traces show the component as downstream in anomalous call chains). That will let us pick the most likely root cause (earliest and most severe faulty component, and — if multiple service-level faults — the most downstream faulty service in traces).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the data already loaded in the kernel (metric anomalies, fault runs, trace anomalies, log aggregates, and error_logs), produce a compact per-candidate summary for these components: [IG01, apache01, Mysql01, Tomcat01, Tomcat02]. For each component, compute the single earliest anomaly timestamp within 2021-03-06 03:30–04:00 across all available sources (metric, trace, log, error_logs). Return one row per component with columns: component, earliest_timestamp_in_window, source_type_of_earliest (metric/trace/log/error_logs), metric_or_trace_or_log_name (the name of that field), anomaly_points_in_window_for_that_source, and severity_or_note (use computed severity if available, else short note like 'NaN' or 'constant-threshold'). Additionally, include a boolean column 'seen_as_downstream_in_trace' which is True if this component appears as the downstream service/container in any anomalous trace row_count or duration anomaly within the window. Sort the output by earliest_timestamp_in_window ascending and limit to these 5 rows. Also return a one-line text recommendation choosing the top candidate component as the likely root cause based on earliest time and greatest severity, and list the exact earliest timestamp to be used as the root-cause occurrence datetime. Keep the output compact (<=5 rows plus the one-line recommendation)."
}

